The department of correctional services has hit back at allegations made by Popcru. It alleged COVID-19 lockdown procedures weren't followed in the process. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The department of correctional services is denying claims its flouting lockdown processes. Police union Popcru accused the department of illegally transferring an inmate to the Upington Correctional Centre. Popcru said in a statement the cross-border transfers are "in contrast with the aims of suppressing the levels of spread of the coronavirus, and cannot be tolerated". READ: COVID-19 prison screening launched "We view these reckless acts as transgressions to the regulations as they flout the set processes, and further put at risk the health of both inmates and correctional officers," the statement read. But the department correctional services says it acted responsibly when it did so and that the transfer was needed. "What was more concerning is some of the unfounded allegations," said department spokesperson Singabakho Nxumalo. READ: SA lockdown: Roadblocks tighten, only essential travel permitted "If they contacted us to check if indeed what was given to them is true, we would have given them factual information." Nxumalo said the department needed to effect the transfer because there was something picked up during a security assessment. "It would have been irresponsible to sit with such information and not act." - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.